Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
loadECO(25.10)                                                  loadECO(25.10)

Name
       loadECO  -  Reads  a  file  containing  ECO  directives and applies the
       changes to the current netlist

Syntax
       loadECO

       [-help]

       [-postMask | -useGACells <GACoreSiteName>]

       [-suffix <suffix>]

       [-verbose]

       <fileName ... >

       Reads a file containing ECO directives and applies the changes  to  the
       current netlist.

       You can use this command at any time after you import the design.

       This  command  also  performs consistency checks while the ECO commands
       are applied and after the changes are complete. It also checks for  and
       observes  power  domains. This command produces results compatible with
       ecoDefIn, so you will use ecoPlace and ecoRoute  to  complete  the  ECO
       process.

       The  ECO  directives  do  not  affect  routing, except in the following
       cases:

              * DELETENET deletes routing attached to a specified deleted net.

              * DELETEINST deletes an instance but leaves the  wires  attached
                to  the  instance dangling. You can then repair dangling wires
                with the router after ECO is complete.

       If you want to reroute the entire design, delete routing before running
       the loadECO command.

       This command supports ECOs for gate array designs through  the  -useGA-
       Cells and -postMask parameters.

       If  an  error  occurs  when the loadECO command reads the ECO file, the
       loadECO command stops without reading more commands from the file,  and
       writes error messages to the innovus.log file.

       Note: The first line of the ECO file you read must be the following:

       FORMATVERSION 2

       For  information  on  the  commands  you can include in the ECO command
       file, see "ECO Directives," in the Innovus User Guide.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each loadECO.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man loadECO

       <fileName>
              Specifies the name of the file that contains the ECO directives.
              You can specify more than one file. File names must be separated
              by one space.

       -suffix
              Specifies the suffix this command adds to spare cells created by
              deleting instances. The default suffix is SPARE.

       -useGACells <GACoreSite>
              Uses  gate  array  cells when adding or deleting instances. This
              parameter applies to gate array  designs  only.  If  ADDINST  is
              specified  in the ECO file, the default behavior for ADDINST ap-
              plies. If DELETEINST is included in the ECO file,  the  software
              deletes an instance if the instance master uses the same site as
              the  specified  <GACoreSite>,  which can be the name of any gate
              array site defined in the LEF file. If you do not  specify  this
              parameter, DELETEINST removes the instance from the netlist.

       -postMask
              When  adding an instance, the new cell will be unplaced. The un-
              placed cell will map to the spare cell during placement with the
              ecoPlace -useSpareCells command.

              When the software deletes an instance, it renames  the  instance
              to  an instance name at the original level of hierarchy, and ap-
              pends the specified suffix. If you do not  specify  the  -suffix
              parameter, this parameter appends SPARE.

       -verbose
              Provides  a report for nets without drivers and the instance in-
              put pins with no net connections.

Example
              * The following command reads myfile and runs the  ECO  commands
                it contains:

                loadECO myfile

              * The loadECO command issues a summary report on completion, for
                example:

       ***************** Load ECO Summary *****************

       Number of New Nets:                             0

       Number of New Instances:                        0

       Number of New Ports:                            0

       Number of New Assigns:                          0

       Number of New Feedthroughs:                     0

       Number of Changed Connections:                  0

       Number of Changed Instances:                    0

       Number of Deleted Nets:                         0

       Number of Deleted Instances:                    1

       Number of Deleted Ports:                        0

       Number of Deleted Assigns:                      0

       Number of Deleted Feedthroughs:                 0

              * The following ECO summary is the output of the loadECO command
                with -verbose options:

       ***************** Load ECO Summary *****************

       Number of New Nets:                                0

       Number of New Instances:                           1

       Number of New Ports:                               0

       Number of New Assigns:                             0

       Number of New Feedthroughs:                        0

       Number of Changed Connections:                     0

       Number of Changed Instances:                       0

       Number of Deleted Nets:                            0

       Number of Deleted Instances:                       0

       Number of Deleted Ports:                           0

       Number of Deleted Assigns:                         0

       Number of Deleted Feedthroughs:                    0

       Nets With No Driver:

               n_23

               u_counter_1/cnt[30]

       Number of Nets With No Drivers:                   2

       Input Instance Pins With No Net Connection:

               A of inst newInst

               TE of inst u_counter_2/ECO_reg_iflg_reg

       Number of Input Instance Pins With No Net Connection:   2

